    id: 39,
    mainHeader: "What's the Value of Viral Fashion?",
    subHeader: "",
    contentHeader: "What's the Value of Viral Fashion?",
    content: "<p class='first'>The fashion industry is currently more focused than ever on creating hype, but a few brands are reconsidering their reliance on marketing gimmicks. In recent years, the fashion industry has shifted its focus from creating classic, timeless pieces to generating buzz and creating viral moments. Many brands rely heavily on marketing stunts to capture the attention of consumers and generate hype around their products. However, some industry experts are questioning the value of viral fashion and whether it truly leads to increased sales and brand loyalty.</p><p>One example of a brand that has rethought its dependence on marketing stunts is Balenciaga. In 2018, the brand released a viral item - a bright yellow oversized puffer jacket that was seen on countless street style stars and influencers. While the jacket generated a lot of buzz, it was ultimately a commercial flop, with many customers balking at its high price tag and impracticality. Since then, Balenciaga has shifted its focus to creating more wearable, timeless pieces, and its sales have reportedly rebounded.</p><p>Another brand that has questioned the value of viral fashion is Vetements. The brand, known for its avant-garde designs and streetwear aesthetic, has become synonymous with viral moments, from its DHL t-shirts to its &quot;No Social Media&quot; collection. However, in a 2020 interview with Vogue, Vetements co-founder Guram Gvasalia admitted that the brand had &quot;overplayed&quot; its hand with these stunts and that it was time to focus on creating more meaningful pieces that would stand the test of time.</p><h3 class='sub-head'>When do we decide Viral fashion has gone too far?</h3><p>Last year, Balenciaga came under fire for an ad campaign that many found disturbing. The ads featured children holding bags that resembled teddy bears, but with studs and harnesses, alongside adult items like wine glasses.</p><p>In a recent interview with Vogue, <strong>Demna</strong>, formerly known as <strong>Demna Gvasalia</strong>, spoke publicly for the first time about the controversial ad campaign. The campaign sparked outrage as it appeared to reference child abuse. Demna apologized for the campaign and explained that the bears were intended to be a reference to punk, not BDSM.</p><p>Although Balenciaga announced that it would sue the company that shot the campaign, Demna acknowledged that he did not know if the reference to child abuse was intentional or not. He expressed regret and stated that the episode fundamentally changed his approach to work, which had previously <em>involved high-profile celebrity endorsements and provocative promotions.</em></p><p>Of course, not all brands are abandoning viral fashion. Off-White, the brainchild of designer Virgil Abloh, has built its entire brand on generating buzz and creating viral moments. From its industrial belt to its &quot;FOR WALKING&quot; boots, Off-White’s designs are often more about making a statement than they are about practicality. And yet, the brand’s sales continue to soar, proving that there is still a market for viral fashion.</p><img src='/images/viral-fashion-2.jpg' alt='kanye' class='block m-auto'/> <p class='text-[12px] text-center py-1 '>OFF-WHITE’s “For -Walking” Sneakers (off---white.com)</p><p>So what is the value of viral fashion? On one hand, it can certainly generate buzz and put a brand in the spotlight. On the other hand, it’s key for brands to consider whether this type of hype is sustainable and whether it actually leads to increased sales and brand loyalty.</p><p>As Balenciaga and Vetements have shown, relying too heavily on viral fashion can be a risky strategy. The key to success in the fashion industry is creating pieces that are both innovative and timeless - items that will stand the test of time and continue to be relevant long after the hype has died down.</p>",
    month: "MAR 2023 EDITION",
    figcaption: "Fashion brands are focusing on creating buzz, but some are reconsidering their reliance on marketing stunts. (GETTY IMAGES)",
    img: "/images/viral-fashion.jpg",
    author: "Omotoyosi Osikoya",
    topics: ["FASHION & BEAUTY", "TRENDS"],
    theme: "filler",
    date: "March 01, 2023",
    template: 3,
    
