    mainHeader: `Pets in the Spotlight: Some Canine Conundrums`,
    subHeader: "",
    contentHeader: `Pets in the Spotlight: Some Canine Conundrums`,
    content: "<p class='first'>As we are celebrating all things canine at Crufts in this March edition of Vell Magazine, we would also like to offer some answers to some of the most common questions that people have asked when trying to understand their dog’s behaviour.</p><h2>Why do dogs dig?</h2><div><img src='/images/canineConundrums-1.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:pt-5 object-contain max-w-[350px]' /><p class='text-center text-sm py-1 max-w-[600px] m-auto'>Image source:<a href='https://www.breakthroughdog.co.uk/articles/health-and-wellbeing/why-do-dogs-dig/'>breakthroughdog.co.uk</a></p></div><p>We cannot blame dogs for digging as it is a deeply ingrained meta-behaviour gained from their wolfish ancestry and, as with any other instinctive behaviours, there is always a very good reason.</p><p>The ground is a natural refrigerator.  Wolves buried food that they couldn’t eat immediately in order to protect themselves and the pack against any future periods of scarcity.  This food is consequently protected from scavengers, either birds or land-based, and the wolf was able to remember the location of the cached food through associative memory and scent. </p><p>Some dogs, particularly if there are more than one dog in the household, will therefore bury ‘food’ such as bones and treats to keep them cool and protected from rival 'predators' in the household.</p><p>Also remember that Terriers or ‘earth dogs’ in Latin, such as the Rat Terrier,  were developed by the Romans to intensify this instinct in order to search for quarry or prey. </p><p> This is also the case with some scent-hounds, such as the Dachshund ‘Badger-Hounds’ in German, whose short powerful legs and long body was adapted perfectly for uncovering and navigating tunnels in search of Badgers.  Any rodents or other small animals burrowing in your yard may well be another trigger for your dog’s digging addiction.</p><p>On very hot days we sometimes consider, in moments of heated despair, sticking our head in the refrigerator door to escape the heat.  Dogs feel the same way, and this is another reason that dogs dig: to surround themselves in the colder earth in order to stay cool in the dog days of summer.</p><p>But there are few things that we can do to prevent or at least mitigate digging in our gardens.  One way is to ensure there is shade for our dogs in hot weather, as well as keeping them cool through regular grooming.</p><h3>Preventing your dog from digging</h3><p>But there are few things that we can do to prevent or at least mitigate digging in our gardens.  One way is to ensure there is shade for our dogs in hot weather, as well as keeping them cool through regular grooming.</p><p>One general method to prevent digging is diversion.  A dog who is bored and mentally and physically under-stimulated will also dig.  The provision of Kongs, puzzle-treats or even a box full of newspapers with goodies such as treats and bones hidden inside all offer excellent diversion.  If there is room, a doggy sandpit offers a way for your dog to scratch this particular itch while protecting your prize roses.</p><p>The other general approach is controlling the environment.  Placing rocks or wiring around areas that you want to protect will usually be effective.  Or even planning your garden to ensure a covering of tough shrubs or hedges in areas which you want to protect.</p><p>Some owners also lace the ground with scents that your dog will find unpleasant or uncomfortable such as coffee, ground or diced peppers or citrus fruit.</p><p>Also be sure to check your yard and the surrounding area for any infestations of rodents or other burrowing wildlife.</p><h2>Why Do Dogs Howl?</h2><div><img src='/images/canineConundrums-2.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:pt-5 object-contain lg:max-w-[500px]' /><p class='text-center text-sm py-1 max-w-[600px] m-auto'>Image source:<a href='https://www.thewildest.com/dog-behavior/why-do-dogs-howl'>Thewildest.com</a></p></div><p>In general dogs howl, like other canids such as wolves and coyotes, as a form of long-distance communication as well as a primal GPS system.</p><p>In the wild wolves and coyotes use this for coordination, but domestic dogs have held on to this as a meta-behaviour in the domesticated world as a way of saying ‘here I am’.  Sadly, for example, dogs suffering from separation anxiety may howl as a long-distance attempt to call their human ‘pack’ in the hope that they will hear and soon return.</p><p>Sometimes this howl can also act as a warning to other roving canids in the wild.  Dogs also use the howl in this way if they see a dog through the window.  This is a ‘hey, get away from my yard’ call used just in case a they are out of range of stern bark</p><p>Wolves would need to coordinate like this during a hunt.  Some breeds of dogs, notably scent-hounds such as a Dachshund, Bloodhounds and Basset Hounds still utilise the howl as hunting dogs as a ‘here I am call’ to their 'pack' of human hunting companions and fellow dogs to alert them to the location of the quarry.</p><p>Also, if a dog is injured or anxious in any way then a howl is a way to draw attention to themselves.  Dogs will therefore still ‘howl in pain’ if they have suffered injury and are in extreme pain.</p><h2>How do I introduce my new dog or puppy to my cats?</h2><div><img src='/images/canineConundrums-3.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:pt-5 object-contain lg:max-w-[450px]' /><p class='text-center text-sm py-1 max-w-[600px] m-auto'>Image source:<a href='https://businessmondays.co.uk/viovet-doubles-veterinary-support-as-covid-19-restrictions-ease/'>businessmondays.co.uk</a></p></div><p>If you really want to stop the fur from flying when you introduce your cute and cuddly bundle of canine joy to your cat, then there are steps you can take to make sure they become the best of furry friends.</p><p>First of all let them follow their noses.  Take the opportunity, if possible, to introduce something that smells of the new puppy like a blanket before the little canine comes home.  This will help offer a non-threatening first impression.</p><p>It is also a good idea that on first meeting the puppy is at its least excitable as possible.  A puppy tired out with a bit of exercise or play will lead to a more relaxed introduction.</p><p>For an untrained puppy, chasing is one of the delights in life.  The puppy should be confined in an area for the first few days, and on a lead when moving around the house.  While on the lead use positive reinforcement (treats and praise) for calmness when the cats are treated with respect rather than a sudden lunge towards them.</p><p>If they do a clear verbal ‘no’ and withhold attention to let the puppy know that his feline friends are a part of his new ‘pack’ and should be respected.</p><p>Always make sure your cats have an escape route.  A cornered cat will not only be highly stressed but could lash out and injure the puppy, setting back the socialisation ‘getting to know you’ process.</p><p>A cat tree or conveniently placed cat shelves will do the trick allowing the cats to look down (possibly both literally and metaphorically) from a safe vantage point on their new canine companion.</p><p>Always take the gradual approach and go back a few steps if either party appears stressed or anxious.</p>",
    month: "APR 2023 EDITION",
    img: "/images/canineConundrums.jpg",
    img_source:"https://www.bentley.edu/sites/default/files/featured_images/2012/03/3065184717_d2e16cccd51.jpg",
    img_source_title:"bentley.edu",
    author: "Colin Hughes",
    topics: ["PETS/ANIMALS", "PETS/ANIMALS IN THE SPOTLIGHT",],
    theme: "",
