    id: 58,
    mainHeader: `How Soulja Boy Used Growth Hacking to Turn "Crank That" into a Triple-Platinum Hit`,
    subHeader: "",
    contentHeader: `How Soulja Boy Used Growth Hacking to Turn "Crank That" into a Triple-Platinum Hit`,
    content: "<p class='first'>Soulja Boy, the American rapper, and producer was only 15 years old when he broke into the music industry with his song 'Crank That.' In 2007, the song quickly rose to the top of the charts, earning triple-platinum status, and even gained the attention of Apple's co-founder Steve Jobs.</p><p>But how did Soulja Boy achieve this level of success without the backing of a record label? The answer is growth hacking.</p><div><img src='/images/souljaBoy-1.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:py-5 object-contain max-w-[750px]'/></div><p>At the time, Soulja Boy had no marketing team or distributor to promote his music. He decided to take matters into his own hands and began studying the Billboard charts to see what songs were popular. He then renamed the audio file of his track to match the trending songs.</p><p>Using Limewire, an illegal file-sharing tool, Soulja Boy uploaded his song 'Crank That' under the false names of other popular songs. This meant that when people searched for a particular song, they would instead download 'Crank That.'</p><p>Soulja Boy's belief was that if people listened to his song, they would fall in love with it, and that's precisely what happened. Within a couple of weeks, 'Crank That' had reached thousands of people and began playing on the radio due to its popularity.</p><p><blockquote class='twitter-tweet p-2 relative max-w-[700px] m-auto'><p lang='en' dir='ltr'>1st rapper with the iPhone 📱 <a href='https://t.co/RwZqGB29xO'></a></p>&mdash; Soulja Boy (Big Draco) (@souljaboy)<span> July 4, 2021</span> <a href='https://twitter.com/souljaboy/status/1411487498778210308?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw' class='absolute bottom-[-20px] sm:bottom-[-10px] right-2'>See on twiter</a></blockquote> <script async src='https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js' charset='utf-8'></script></p><p>As the song gained traction, record labels started approaching Soulja Boy, desperate to sign what had become the hottest artist of the moment. 'Crank That' even broke records on iTunes as one of the most downloaded songs of the era.</p><p>Big Draco stated in a ‘Million Dollaz Worth of Game podast’:</p><p><i>“I was the first rapper with the iPhone,” Soulja Boy calmly states as the hosts of the podcasts erupt into laughter in disbelief. “It was ‘Crank Dat’ video shoot 2007. Steve Jobs and the Apple team came. I was in the swimming pool, doing the instructional dance. Showing the people how to do the dance. We was on the set of the ‘Crank Dat’ video. They came, they brought me the iPhone.”</i></p><div><img src='/images/souljaBoy-3.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:py-5 object-contain max-w-[350px]'/><p class='text-md text-center font-semibold'><a href='https://www.instagram.com/reel/CQ4KcpDncQi/?utm_source=ig_embed&ig_rid=bf75043e-c67f-4b16-a66b-12c7cf6c354a'>View more</a></p></div><p>The buzz surrounding Soulja Boy's success even caught the attention of Apple's Steve Jobs, who invited him to the company's headquarters. Jobs personally gave Soulja Boy the very first iPhone, which the rapper held up in his viral music video, further capitalizing on the marketing opportunity.</p><p>Soulja Boy's success story is a testament to the power of growth hacking, which involves creative and unconventional methods to grow a business or brand. By thinking outside the box and using tactics like renaming audio files and leveraging peer-to-peer sharing networks, Soulja Boy was able to turn 'Crank That' into a cultural phenomenon that would go down in history.</p>",
    month: "APR 2023 EDITION",
    img: "/images/souljaBoy.jpg",
    img_source:"https://www.sohh.com/5-times-soulja-boy-influential-impact-on-hip-hop/",
