    id: 71,
    mainHeader: `Does A Woman Need Half of Her Husband's Wealth To Be Happy?`,
    subHeader: "",
    contentHeader: `Does A Woman Need Half of Her Husband's Wealth To Be Happy?`,
    content: "<p class='first'>The recent divorce story of Moroccan footballer Achraf Hakimi has caused quite a stir in the media. His ex-wife Hiba Abouk, who reportedly asked for half of his fortune in the divorce settlement, discovered that there was nothing in his name to claim.</p><p>According to recent reports, high-profile divorces in the world of sports are becoming increasingly common, with some women seeking to claim a significant portion of their former partner's wealth. The cases of former Arsenal player Emmanuel Eboue and Moroccan footballer Achraf Hakimi are two such examples that have sparked intense debate.</p><p>Eboue's ex-wife Aurelie filed for divorce in 2017, claiming half of his wealth. The couple had been married for over a decade and had three children together. However, after a difficult legal battle, it was revealed that Eboue had lost all of his wealth due to a combination of financial mismanagement and a contentious divorce settlement. The former player was left homeless and struggling to rebuild his life.</p><div><img src='/images/eboue.jpg' class='block m-auto  md:pt-5 object-contain lg:max-w-[450px]' /><p class='text-center text-sm py-1 max-w-[600px] m-auto'>Image source:<a href='https://www.standardmedia.co.ke/entertainment/news/article/2001398809/lessons-from-the-tragic-story-of-emmanuelle-eboue'>The Standard</a></p></div><p>On the other hand, Achraf Hakimi's ex-wife Hiba Abouk recently tried to claim half of his fortune in their divorce settlement, only to discover that he had nothing in his name. This revelation caused a stir on social media, with some applauding Hakimi for being financially savvy, while others criticized him for not being honest with his partner.</p><p>The question that arises from these cases is whether a woman needs to claim half of her partner's wealth to be happy. While some argue that it is only fair for the partner who supported their spouse to claim a portion of their wealth, others believe that such claims can be excessive and unfair.</p><p>These cases are not limited to sports stars alone. Many successful men in various industries have faced similar challenges in their relationships. There is a growing concern that a lot of women get intos relationships to 	&quot;secure the bag,&quot; or to gain financial security through a partner rather than building their own wealth. Some men are known for this too, not just as common. Relationships should be based on trust, respect, and mutual support, rather than financial gain. While it is understandable for anyone to want to protect their assets, it is crucial to approach the issue of finances and divorce settlements with fairness and transparency.</p><p>In the case of Eboue, his struggles serve as a cautionary tale about the importance of sound financial planning and seeking legal advice during divorce proceedings. It is also worth noting that despite the hardships he faced, Eboue eventually moved on and found a way to rebuild his life.</p><p>For Hakimi, in a shocking turn of events, Hiba has now been ordered to give half of her net worth to Hakimi after filing for divorce. (Source: <a href='https://www.instagram.com/p/CrFDOXQsLHC/?utm_source=ig_embed&ig_rid=50647459-12b7-4a95-93ac-25ab10804a8f'>@wealth</a> on Instagram)</p><p>Witnessing the outrage on social media, it’s clear that the debate around the issue of divorce settlements and financial claims will continue to rage on. I’d say it is crucial to approach these issues with empathy and understanding, recognizing that each situation is unique and requires a fair and transparent approach.</p>",
    month: "APR 2023 EDITION",
    img: "/images/hakimi.jpg",
    img_source: "https://english.elpais.com/spain/2023-03-28/hiba-abouk-breaks-silence-after-achraf-hakimi-accused-of-rape-i-will-always-be-on-the-side-of-the-victims.html",
    img_source_title: "Getty Images",
    author: "Omotoyosi Osikoya",
    topics: ["LIFE MATTERS", "COST OF LIVING"],
    theme: "filler",
    date: "April 20 2023",
